The '''Bakoko''', also known as the '''Basoo''', are an ethnic group in [[Cameroon]]. According to 2010 figures there are around 111,000 of them, mostly concentrated in the [[Littoral Region (Cameroon)|Littoral Region]] in the southwest of the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joshuaproject.net/people-profile.php?peo3=10593&rog3=CM|title=Bakoko people|publisher=Joshua Project|accessdate=28 August 2012}}</ref> They speak the [[Bakoko language]], which is a [[Bantu language]], and are related to the [[Bassa people (Cameroon)|Bassa people]].<ref name="AppiahGates2010">{{cite book|last1=Appiah|first1=Anthony|last2=Gates|first2=Henry Louis|title=Encyclopedia of Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A0XNvklcqbwC&pg=PA148|accessdate=28 August 2012|date=17 February 2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-533770-9|page=148}}</ref><ref name="Fanso1989">{{cite book|last=Fanso|first=Verkijika G.|title=Cameroon History for Secondary Schools and Colleges: Prehistoric times to the nineteenth century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dqUPAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=28 August 2012|date=31 July 1989|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=978-0-333-47121-0|page=49}}</ref> These people put up a resistance to the Germans when they invaded in 1889.<ref name="JonassohnBjörnson1998">{{cite book|last1=Jonassohn|first1=Kurt|last2=Björnson|first2=Karin Solveig|title=Genocide and Gross Human Rights Violations in Comparative Perspective|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jIxCUXI38zcC&pg=PA250|accessdate=28 August 2012|year=1998|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-0-7658-0417-4|page=250}}</ref>

