The '''Deutscher Bridge-Verband''' (DBV, [[Germany|German]] [[Duplicate bridge|Bridge]] Association) is an association for bridge players and bridge clubs in Germany. It was founded in 1949 and comprises 14 regional associations with about 28,000 members (out of around 500,000 bridge players in Germany) and about 470 clubs. The DBV promotes bridge in Germany and represents the country at the international level.

[[Category:Clubs and societies in Germany]]

{{Germany-org-stub}}

{{Infobox official post|post=Judicial Complaints Reviewer|type=[[Ombudsman]]|appointer=[[Cabinet Secretary for Justice]]|first=Gillian Thompson|incumbent=Gillian Thompson|website=http://www.judicialcomplaintsreviewer.org.uk/|formation=2014|constituting_instrument=Judiciary and Courts (Scotland) Act 2008|incumbentsince=1 September 2014}}{{Scots law|expanded=Administration}} The '''Judicial Complaints Reviewer''' is not a Scottish [[public ombudsman]], as the role does not carry ombudsman powers of redress. The JCR is responsible for reviewing the handling of complaints against the [[judiciary of Scotland]] by the [[Judicial Office for Scotland]]. The post was established in 2011 as a result of the [[Judiciary and Courts (Scotland) Act 2008]]. The Reviewer is appointed by the [[Cabinet Secretary for Justice]], with the approval of the [[Lord President of the Court of Session]]. The Reviewer's services are open to those who have complained about the conduct of a member of the judiciary, and also to members of the judiciary who have been the subject of a complaint.
The first Judicial Complaints Reviewer was Moi Ali, 2011-2014 and the second was Gillian Thompson; who was appointed on 1 September 2014. The third reviewer takes up the role on 1st September 2017.
==Remit and jurisdiction== Complaints about the conduct, both within and outwith the [[courts of Scotland]], of [[Judiciary of Scotland|judicial officer holders]] in Scotland are made to the Lord President through the Judicial Office for Scotland. However, the Judicial Office does not consider complaints about judicial decisions which are dealt with through [[appeal]]s.<ref name="complaints">{{cite web|title=Complaints About Court Judiciary - You and the Judiciary - Judiciary of Scotland|url=http://www.scotland-judiciary.org.uk/15/0/Complaints|website=www.scotland-judiciary.org.uk|format=PDF|publisher=Judicial Office for Scotland|accessdate=4 April 2017|date=2017}}</ref>
The office of the Judicial Complaints Reviewer was established by Section 30 of the [[Judiciary and Courts (Scotland) Act 2008]]<ref name="act2008s30">{{cite web|title=Judiciary and Courts (Scotland) Act 2008 (Section 30)|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2008/6/section/30|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|publisher=The National Archives|accessdate=4 April 2017|language=en|date=29 October 2008}}</ref> The Reviewer's role is to review how complaints regarding members of [[judiciary of Scotland|the judiciary]] have been handled by the [[Judicial Office for Scotland]] in accordance with the complaint rules laid down by the Lord President. As of May 2017, complaints should be handled in line with Complaints About the Judiciary (Scotland) Rules 2017.<ref name="rules2017">{{cite web|title=Complaints About the Judiciary (Scotland) Rules 2017|url=http://www.scotland-judiciary.org.uk/Upload/Documents/ComplaintsabouttheJudiciaryScotlandRules2017_1.pdf|website=scotland-judiciary.org.uk|publisher=Judicial Office for Scotland|accessdate=4 April 2017|date=31 March 2017}}</ref> She cannot change the outcome of the investigation, overturn a decision, or initiate redress. However, where she finds a fault in the process she passes a referral to the Lord President who then makes decision.<ref name="howcomplain">{{cite web|title=How to complain|url=http://www.judicialcomplaintsreviewer.org.uk/how-complain|website=www.judicialcomplaintsreviewer.org.uk|publisher=Judicial Complaints Reviewer|accessdate=4 April 2017|language=en}}</ref>
==Judicial Complaints Reviewer==
Moi Ali became the first ever JCR on 1 September 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.journalonline.co.uk/News/1010107.aspx#.WZr7YsaZPow|title=Judicial Complaints Reviewer appointed : The Journal Online|last=|first=|date=|website=www.journalonline.co.uk|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-23}}</ref> She established the office and pushed for greater powers, claiming that the role was "window-dressing" and the judicial watchdog had no teeth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/justice-secretary-kenny-macaskill-urged-2928766|title=Justice secretary Kenny MacAskill urged to improve scrutiny of Scotland's judges after claims they stifle public complaints|last=Findlay|first=Russell|date=2013-12-15|work=dailyrecord|access-date=2018-05-23}}</ref> She did not seek reappointment after the end of her three-year term, as she was dissatisfied with the powers of the role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13142428.Judicial_watchdog_quits_from__straightjacket__role/|title=Judicial watchdog quits from 'straightjacket' role|website=HeraldScotland|language=en|access-date=2018-05-23}}</ref> Gillian Thompson became the second Judicial Complaints Reviewer on 1 September 2014, and she too did not serve a second term of office.<ref name="appointment">{{cite web|title=New Judicial Complaints Reviewer appointed|url=http://news.scotland.gov.uk/News/Judicial-Complaints-Reviewer-103e.aspx|publisher=The Scottish Government|accessdate=23 October 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023045045/http://news.scotland.gov.uk/News/Judicial-Complaints-Reviewer-103e.aspx|archivedate=23 October 2014|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/opinion/15470417.Sunday_Herald_View__Scrutiny_of_judiciary__must_be_taken_seriously/|title=Sunday Herald View: Scrutiny of judiciary must be taken seriously|website=HeraldScotland|language=en|access-date=2018-05-23}}</ref>
