[[Albania]] is an ethnically homogeneous country, where the overwhelming majority of the population speaks [[Albanian language|Albanian]], which is also the official language. It has two distinct dialects: [[Tosk]], spoken in the south, and [[Gheg]], spoken in the north. However many [[Albanians]] speak [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Greek language|Greek]], [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], [[English language|English]] amongst other languages too, due to the high numbers of Albanian diaspora and Albanian communities throughout the Balkans.

Albania is one of the most polyglot nations in Europe.<ref name="Gloyer">{{cite book|last=Gloyer|first=Gillian|title=Albania: the Bradt travel guide|year=2008|publisher=Bradt Travel Guides|location=Chalfont St. Peter|isbn=9781841622460|edition=3rd|page=44}}</ref> Many Albanians at home, in the region and around the world speak more than two languages. [[Italian language|Italian]] is widely spoken throughout Albania. [[Greek language|Greek]], the language of the Greek minority of the south, is also very widespread in that region. Nowadays, knowledge of [[English language|English]] is growing very rapidly, especially among the youth. Various languages are spoken by ethnic minorities: [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]], etc.

==Status of Albanian==
{{bar box
|float = left
|title = Distribution of languages of Albania
|bars =
