{{see also|Aromanian people#In Albania|}}

[[Aromanian language|Aromanian]] is the native language for about 100,000 to 200,000 [[Aromanians]] of [[Albania]].<ref>According to [http://www.intereg.org/ INTEREG] - quoted by [http://www.eurominority.org/version/eng/index.asp Eurominority] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060703040707/http://www.eurominority.org/version/eng/index.asp |date=2006-07-03 }}: [http://www.eurominority.eu/version/eng/minority-detail.asp?id_minorities=296 Aromanians in Albania] {{webarchive|url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20141122043814/http%3A//www.eurominority.eu/version/eng/minority%2Ddetail.asp?id_minorities%3D296 |date=2014-11-22 }}, [http://www.albanien.ch/nla/26/art262.html Albania's Aromanians; Reemerging into History]</ref><ref name=Tanner>Arno Tanner. [https://books.google.com/books?id=EQtCPAo1XU8C&pg=PA208&dq=200000%2Baromanians%2Bwinnifrith&hl=el&ei=VZbxTK-OHMSgOomY_ZMK&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAw#v=snippet&q=200000%2Baromanian&f=false The forgotten minorities of Eastern Europe: the history and today of selected ethnic groups in five countries]. East-West Books, 2004 {{ISBN|978-952-91-6808-8}}, p. 218: "In Albania, Vlachs are estimated to number as many as 200,000"</ref> They mostly live in the southern and central regions of the country. The Aromanians, under the name "Vlachs", are a recognized [[minority group|cultural minority]] in the Albanian law.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schwandner-Sievers|first=Stephanie|title=The Albanian Aromanians´ Awakening: Identity Politics and Conflicts in Post-Communist Albania|url=http://www.ecmi.de/uploads/tx_lfpubdb/working_paper_3.pdf|publisher=European Centre for Minority Issues|accessdate=13 November 2012}}</ref>

===Macedonian===
{{see also|Macedonians of Albania}}

According to the 1989 census, there were approximately 5,000 [[Macedonian language]]-speakers in Albania. Most of these people live in the southeastern part of the country in the [[Lake Prespa]] region.<ref name="1989 census">{{cite web|url=http://www.fes.hr/E-books/pdf/Local%20Self%20Government/09.pdf |title=LOCAL SELF-GOVERNMENT AND DECENTRALIZATION: CASE OF ALBANIA. HISTORY, REFORMES AND CHALLENGES |accessdate=16 November 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025205442/https://www.fes.hr/E-books/pdf/Local%20Self%20Government/09.pdf |archivedate=25 October 2012 |df= }}</ref> Macedonians are an officially recognized minority in the [[Pustec Municipality]]. However, only the Macedonians living in Pustec are allowed to declare their nationality and language. Ethnic Macedonian organization claim that 120.000 to 350,000 Macedonians live in Albania.<ref>{{cite web|author=United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees |url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/country,,MRGI,,ALB,,49749d65b,0.html |title=World Directory of Minorities and Indigenous Peoples - Albania : Macedonians |publisher=Unhcr.org |accessdate=2013-07-26}}</ref> They are politically represented by the ''Alliance of Macedonians for European Integration'', which in the 2011 elections received ~2,500 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cec.org.al/images/stories/Legjislacioni_2011/Vendime_2011/VENDIM%201229/Lidhja%202.pdf|title=Results of the 2011 local elections of Albania|year=2011|publisher=Central Elections Commission of Albania|accessdate=14 December 2012}}</ref>

===Romani===
{{see also|Vlax Romani language}}
About 10,000 [[Romani people]] live in Albania today. They have preserved the language, despite the lack of education in that language.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hemming|first=Andreas|title=Albania: family, society and culture in the 20th century|year=2010|publisher=LIT|location=Münster|isbn=9783643501448|page=132}}</ref>

===Serbo-Croatian===
[[Serbo-Croatian language|Serbo-Croatian]] is mostly spoken and understood in northern Albania, near the border of former Yugoslavian countries of Serbia and Montenegro.<ref name="Gloyer"/> The television phenomenon of Italian also happened to Serbo-Croatian, but to a lesser extent.<ref name="Hemming">{{cite book|last=Hemming|first=Andreas|title=Albania: family, society and culture in the 20th century|year=2010|publisher=LIT|location=Münster|isbn=9783643501448|page=183}}</ref>

==Foreign languages==
The most-widely foreign languages spoken in Albania are English, Italian and Greek.

A new study carried out by [[Eurostat]], the statistical agency of the [[European Union]], analyzed the demography of the adult population 25-64 of several european countries as of 2016. The results of the Adult Education Survey, released in May 2018, showed that the 39.9 % of the 25-64 years old is able to use at least one foreign language. The main foreign language known is English with 40.0%, followed by Italian with 27.8% and Greek with 22.9 %. The English speakers were mostly young people, the knowledge of Italian is stable in every age group, while there is a decrease of the speakers of Greek in the youngest group. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.instat.gov.al/media/4028/adult-education-survey-2017.pdf|title=Press release of the Adult Education Survey|last=|first=|date=10 May 2018|work=Albanian Institute of Statistics|access-date=23 May 2018}}</ref>

===Italian===
[[Italian language|Italian]] is by far the best-known foreign language in Albania and used to have official status when the country was a protectorate of Italy.<ref name="Gloyer"/>  Most Italian-speakers have not learnt the language in classrooms or from books, but rather by watching Italian television.<ref name="Hemming"/> During the late [[People's Socialist Republic of Albania|communist regime]], Albanians living in the towns along the [[Adriatic Sea]] coast had access to Italian television.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pardo-de-Santayana|first=Manuel|title=Ethnobotany in the new Europe : people, health, and wild plant resources|year=2010|publisher=Berghahn Books|location=New York|isbn=9781845454562|edition=1. publ.|author2=Pieroni, Andrea |author3=Puri, Rajindra K. |page=29}}</ref>  Many Albanians "grew skilled at rewiring their TVs to overcome [the] Albanian government's attempt to block Italian channels".<ref name="McAdam">{{cite book|last=McAdam|first=Marika|title=Western Balkans|year=2009|publisher=Lonely Planet|location=Footscray, Vic.|isbn=9781741047295|edition=2nd |author2=Jayne d' Arcy |author3=Chris Deliso |author4=Peter Dragicevic|page=96}}</ref> A large number of middle-aged and younger people grew up with the language and know it very well.<ref name="Gloyer"/>

Among the elderly, Italian is also common as the language was used in the educational system in the 1930s, after [[Zog of Albania|King Zog]] released a decree requiring all Albanian schools to teach Italian in 1933.{{sfn|Rista-Dema|2006|p=14}}

Albania also is home to 19,000 ethnic Italians, who have aided the growth of the language in the country.

===English===
[[English language|English]] is mostly popular among the younger generations of Albanians.<ref>{{cite book|last=Vorhees|first=Mara|title=Eastern Europe.|year=2009|publisher=Lonely Planet|location=Footscray, Vic.|isbn=9781741048544|edition=10th|page=43}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Albania Company Laws and Regulations Handbook|year=2008|publisher=Int'l Business Publications|isbn=9781433069338|author=IBP USA Staff, International Business Publications, USA|page=228}}</ref> Since the 1990s it is the most-taught foreign language in the Albanian educational system. As of 2006, more than 65% of Albanian children could speak fluent or semi-fluent English.{{sfn|Rista-Dema|2006|p=16}}

The language came to Albania in 1921, when the Albanian Vocational School started to teach English with the sponsorship of the [[American Red Cross]]. The school operated until 1933.{{sfn|Rista-Dema|2006|p=14}} The [[Principality of Albania|Albanian Government at the time]] decided to make English the country's second language.{{sfn|Rista-Dema|2006|p=12}} Russian became the major language taught in schools after the Communists took control over the country. After the [[Soviet-Albanian Split]] in the 1960s, English came to compete with Russian.{{sfn|Rista-Dema|2006|p=14}} A 2006 book by Mimoza Rista-Dema, a Ph.D. in Linguistics at [[Indiana University]], describes the teaching of English during the communist era:
{{cquote|Although English was taught at schools, it was considered the language of Western imperialism and as a result, elements of its culture and civilization were offered to English learners selectively.{{sfn|Rista-Dema|2006|p=15}}}}

===Other===
French [[lycées]] in [[Korçë]] and [[Gjirokastër]] operated during the communist era, because long-time leader of [[People's Socialist Republic of Albania|Communist Albania]], [[Enver Hoxha]] studied in the [[University of Montpellier]] in France and upon his rise to power allowed their activity. Albania is a member of [[la Francophonie]]. Most French-speakers in Albania can be found in these two towns and surrounding areas, but also elsewhere in the country.<ref name="Gloyer"/> According to La Francophonie, Albania is home to 300,000 French speakers.

[[Russian language|Russian]] began to be taught in schools and universities in the 1950s, when it was ''[[lingua franca]]'' of the [[Eastern Bloc]] countries, part of which was Albania.{{sfn|Rista-Dema|2006|p=14}} It continued until the [[Soviet–Albanian split]] in early 1961. Many who learnt in at the time, have forgotten most of it due to lack of usage.<ref name="Gloyer"/>

After the ideological controversies with the USSR, [[Socialist People's Republic of Albania#Albania and China|Albania and China became closer]]. A number of Albanians studied in China and learnt Chinese there. After the [[Fall of communism in Albania|collapse of communism in Albania]] in 1991, many young Albanians also traveled to China for education and learned the language.<ref name="Gloyer"/>

